<PageLayout
  title="Bremelanotide + tirzepatide (BMT-801): pairing an MC4R agonist with a GLP-1 to hold weight off"
  kicker="Investigational"
  description="Palatin's BMT-801 study paired a low dose of the MC4R agonist bremelanotide with the GLP-1/GIP drug tirzepatide. It met its Phase 2 endpoint — but the striking result was weight-regain: halted in the melanocortin group after treatment stopped."
  updated="2026"
  about={[
    { name: 'Bremelanotide', type: 'Drug', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bremelanotide'] },
    { name: 'Tirzepatide', type: 'Drug', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tirzepatide'] },
    { name: 'Obesity', type: 'MedicalCondition', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Obesity'] },
  ]}
>
  <KeyTakeaways
    items={[
      'BMT-801 is Palatin’s investigational obesity combination: a low dose of the MC4R agonist bremelanotide co-administered with the GLP-1/GIP drug tirzepatide.',
      'It engages two appetite systems at once — the melanocortin circuit and the gut-hormone circuit — using low doses of each.',
      'The 8-week Phase 2 study met its primary endpoint with high statistical significance, producing about 4.4% weight loss.',
      'The standout result was weight-regain: after stopping, the tirzepatide-only group regained over half the lost weight in two weeks, but regain was effectively halted in the group that also got bremelanotide.',
      'Low-dose bremelanotide matched tirzepatide on appetite suppression, with no added safety concerns.',
    ]}
  />

  <p>
    This is the melanocortin system meeting the blockbuster obesity drugs on purpose. Palatin's
    <strong>BMT-801</strong> study paired a low dose of the MC4R agonist
    <a href="/bremelanotide">bremelanotide</a> with <strong>tirzepatide</strong> — the
    GLP-1/GIP drug behind Mounjaro and Zepbound — to see whether hitting two appetite systems at
    once beats leaning hard on either alone.<Cite n={1} />
  </p>

  <h2>Two appetite systems, low doses of each</h2>
  <p>
    Tirzepatide works through gut-hormone (GLP-1 and GIP) circuits; bremelanotide works through
    the brain's <a href="/receptors/mc4r">MC4R</a> melanocortin circuit. They are different
    routes to the same destination — reduced appetite — which is exactly why combining them is
    interesting: you might get the effect of both while keeping the dose of each low enough to
    limit side effects.<Cite n={1} /> The <a href="/glp1-appetite">GLP-1 and melanocortin
    pathways</a> are already known to intersect, so pairing them is less a gamble than a
    hypothesis with a mechanism behind it.
  </p>

  <h2>The Phase 2 result</h2>
  <p>
    The 8-week Phase 2 study met its primary endpoint with high statistical significance:
    low doses of both drugs produced about <strong>4.4% weight loss</strong>, and — notably —
    low-dose bremelanotide <strong>matched tirzepatide on appetite suppression</strong>, with no
    added safety or tolerability concerns.<Cite n={1} /><Cite n={2} /> For a combination using
    reduced doses, matching the established drug on appetite is a meaningful signal.
  </p>

  <h2>The result that matters most: holding weight off</h2>
  <p>
    The headline finding wasn't the weight lost but the weight <em>kept off</em>. Weight regain
    after stopping a GLP-1 drug is one of the biggest problems in obesity medicine — the pounds
    come back. In BMT-801, after treatment stopped, the tirzepatide-only group regained
    <strong>more than half</strong> of its lost weight within two weeks. But in the group that
    also received bremelanotide, <strong>weight regain was effectively halted</strong>.<Cite n={2} />
    That points to melanocortin activation doing something GLP-1 drugs struggle with: helping the
    body <em>defend</em> a lower weight rather than snap back toward the old one. If it holds up,
    it addresses one of the field's central unmet needs.
  </p>

  <h2>The honest bottom line</h2>
  <p>
    BMT-801 is a Phase 2 signal, not a finished drug — an 8-week study with modest weight loss by
    design, since the point was low-dose combination rather than maximal loss. But the
    weight-regain result is the kind of finding that could reframe how melanocortin drugs fit into
    obesity care: not as another way to lose weight, but as a way to keep it off after a GLP-1
    does the losing. For the melanocortin half of the pair, see
    <a href="/bremelanotide">bremelanotide</a>; for the intersection it exploits, see
    <a href="/glp1-appetite">GLP-1 drugs & appetite</a>; for the oral MC4R drug chasing the same
    space, see <a href="/pl-7737">PL-7737</a>.
  </p>

